Explanation:
- I parsed routes defined on the Express router in routes/userRoutes.js. Each router.route(...).method(...) chain can register multiple HTTP methods for the same path; I expanded those into separate API entries (one entry per HTTP method + path).
- The literal path strings extracted from the source are "/", "/auth", "/logout", "/profile", and "/:id". Per your requirement, Express-style path parameters (":id") were converted to OpenAPI-style "{id}" in the output.
- The listed handlers (registerUser, getUsers, authUser, logoutUser, getUserProfile, updateUserProfile, deleteUser, getUserById, updateUser) are the final controller functions invoked for each route in this file. There are middleware functions used on some routes (protect, admin) but those are not the final request handlers; they are imported and not implemented in this file.
- For all entries:
  - implementationPresentInSameFile is false because the handler functions are imported from ../controllers/userController.js (and middleware from ../middleware/authMiddleware.js), not defined in this file.
  - isPathLiteral is true because the path strings appear directly as literal strings in this file.
  - isPathDerivedFromConvention is false because Express routes here are explicit, not inferred from names.
  - isPathPrefix is false because the strings represent the route path at this router level (I did not assume any mounting prefix from other files).
  - isRest is true because these are RESTful user-management endpoints (CRUD and auth).
  - isTest is false as none of these appear to be test-only routes.

I did not include any routes for which the path is not explicitly present in this file.

path.description: The HTTP request path, which must begin with a forward slash (/) and have path parameters wrapped in curly braces ({}). Set this to null if it cannot be determined.

handler.description: The function, class, class method, or object that handles the HTTP request. Use exactly "anonymous" to denote an anonymous implementation.
handler.title: Handler

handler_in_same_file.description: Whether the handler's implementation is present in the same source code file, rather than being imported.

path_is_prefix.title: Path Is Prefix
